  "title": "DigiDNA",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f73462e2180be67c",
      "text": "Governments around the world spy on their critics – journalists, human rights activists, opposition activists: The international revelation series \"Pegasus Project\" was in the headlines around the world. At the center of the research was the spy software Pegasus from the Israeli company NSO.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "53163e3591e466f8",
      "text": "The program is capable of infecting smartphones from a distance. A secret service or police agency that has a Pegasus license usually only needs the phone number of a target person to attack their smartphone. Pegasus then turns the phone into a digital bug and takes complete control of the device. All data and any communication can be viewed, stolen and analyzed by police and intelligence officers, even encrypted chats.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f70c56dfcb0a1ce1",
      "text": "The [[iMazing]] software  now offers a way for at least iPhone users to scan their device for traces of a Pegasus infection. iMazing is a program for managing Apple devices. The function to detect spyware is free of charge. The software was developed by the Swiss company [[DigiDNA]]. Founded in Geneva in 2008, the company has eight employees in Switzerland. The fact that they were able to develop the new spyware detection function is thanks to Amnesty International's IT team.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3f5d3d027c76c226",
      "text": "Security researchers have been examining every line of Pegasus code they find on affected smartphones for years. They also map the infrastructure of the manufacturer NSO, i.e. the servers and their IP addresses through which the spyware is downloaded. This has resulted in a worldwide exchange of known attack routes. Crucial parts of the program code were thus also developed by IT forensic experts at Amnesty International's Security Lab and published as open source software on the web for free use as part of the Pegasus project.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "dc6cf0a1b2abe68f",
      "text": "The Swiss software now builds on this, as DigiDNA co-owner and developer Gregorio Zanon tells this newspaper [Basler Zeitung ; R.B.]. \"I heard on the radio on the way home that Amnesty International had published the code. That's when I very quickly called my business partners and told them we had to do it,\" Zanon said. Because the program published by Amnesty is very technical and not manageable for normal citizens, he said.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6fb39782da36011b",
      "text": "\"We worked on it for two weeks, I didn't sleep very much,\" Zanon says. Now the application is available in eleven languages and is in hot demand. \"We have a lot of downloads, but that was to be expected,\" says Zanon.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "89032646c837cead",
      "text": "How does the program work? If users want to use the Pegasus scan, they have to create a backup of their iPhone for the program or allow iMazing to access an existing backup. The software then searches for traces of Pegasus in this data. These can be found in chat messages, in search histories in the browser or in log files of the operating system. The software thus searches through the most private information. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fade1a83f563a699",
      "text": "The developers emphasize that no data is transferred and the analysis takes place exclusively on the user's computer. However, users should not be lulled into a false sense of security after checking their iPhones, the developer warns. \"Spyware develops quickly. We can only detect malware if it is already known and documented. A negative result is never a guarantee of security,\" Zanon says."
    },
